06536nam a22008655i 9780231555401DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021040026  a97802315554017 a10.7312/moin204162doi  a(DE-B1597)627875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL65.K55 7aHIS0370002bisacsh  aNT 31102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/131050:00aSacred Kingship in World History :bBetween Immanence and Transcendence /ced. by A. Azfar Moin, Alan Strathern. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Sacred Kingship in World History: Between Immanence and Transcendence -- t2. Kings Before Kingship: The Politics of the Enchanted Universe -- t3. Immanence in the Andes (1000–1700 ce): Divine Kingship, Stranger-Kingship, and Diarchy -- t4 Gods and Kings in Ancient Mesopotamia -- t5 Pharaonic Kingship and Its Biblical Deconstruction -- t6 King, Divinity, and Law in Ancient Greece -- t7. Humanizing the Divine and Divinizing the Human in Early China: Comparative Reflections on Ritual, Sacrifice, and Sovereignty -- t8 Caliphal Sovereignty or the Immanence of Transcendence -- t9. Neoplatonic Kingship in the Islamic World: Akbar’s Millennial History -- t10. Hobbes the Egyptian: The Return to Pharaoh, or the Ancient Roots of Secular Politics -- t11. Ancient Apostasy, Modern Drama: Henrik Ibsen’s Emperor and Galilean -- t12. The Last Hindu King: How Nepal Desanctified Its Monarchy -- t13. A Caliphate Beyond Politics: The Sovereignty of ISIS -- t14. Sacred Kingship: A Synthesis -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSacred kingship has been the core political form, in small-scale societies and in vast empires, for much of world history. This collaborative and interdisciplinary book recasts the relationship between religion and politics by exploring this institution in long-term and global comparative perspective.Editors A. Azfar Moin and Alan Strathern present a theoretical framework for understanding sacred kingship, which leading scholars reflect on and respond to in a series of essays. They distinguish between two separate but complementary religious tendencies, immanentism and transcendentalism, which mold kings into divinized or righteous rulers, respectively. Whereas immanence demands priestly and cosmic rites from kings to sustain the flourishing of life, transcendence turns the focus to salvation and subordinates rulers to higher ethical objectives. Secular modernity does not end the struggle between immanence and transcendence—flourishing and righteousness—but only displaces it from kings onto nations and individuals. After an essay by Marshall Sahlins that ranges from the Pacific to the Arctic, the book contains chapters on religion and kingship in settings as far-flung as ancient Egypt, classical Greece, medieval Islam, Mughal India, modern European drama, and ISIS. Sacred Kingship in World History sheds new light on how religion has constructed rulership, with implications spanning global history, religious studies, political theory, and anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aImmanence (Philosophy) 0aKings and rulersxReligious aspects. 0aMonarchyxHistory. 0aReligion and politics. 0aTranscendence (Philosophy) 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aAssmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrisch, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevji, Faisal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellner, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https